NEWS: Our correspondents worldwide report
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: US lead slips in world=92s top 100 universities

David Jobbins and Karen MacGregor
American universities continued to lead the latest Academic Ranking of
World Universities, but US dominance of the global top 100 list compiled by
China=92s Shanghai Jiao Tong University slipped this year, to 54 institutio=
ns
against 67 in 2009. Harvard clinched the top slot, as it has since the
ranking was first published in 2003.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813204958643

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Work begins on OECD student assessment

Ian R Dobson*
The Australian Council for Educational Research has been assessing higher
education in the country for years, but now it has moved onto the world
stage. ACER is leading a feasibility study into the first global assessment
of students=92 knowledge and skills, the OECD=92s Assessment of Higher
Education Learning Outcomes, AHELO.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813204830617

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

TAIWAN: Top students head for China

Yojana Sharma
Taiwan=92s parliament will again be debating a stalled bill to open its
universities to students from mainland China, after months of disruption
and filibustering by the Opposition. But already Taiwanese students are
going the other way.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813204448517

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CANADA: Government axes more data collection

Philip Fine
The Canadian government is again under fire, as it appears to be further
weakening the ability of policy-makers and lobby groups to assess the
country=92s performance in the higher education sector. Three more key
data-collection tools have been cancelled or are being re-examined for
their relevance and cost-effectiveness.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010081320433311

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

IRELAND: Big investment boost for research

John Walshe
The largest research investment plan in the history of the Republic of
Ireland =96 EUR359 million (US$473 million) =96 is aimed at transforming the
country into =91Europe=92s innovation hub=92, according to Brian Cowen, the=
 Irish
Prime Minister. His support for the investment is an indication of how
seriously the government is hoping the so-called =91smart economy=92 will d=
rag
the country out of its current economic mess.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813204218205

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

RUSSIA: Government seeks academic staff skills boost

Eugene Vorotnikov
The Russian government, unhappy with the current skill levels of
university professors and teachers, is planning to improve the proficiency
of academics by encouraging their more active engagement in scientific work
and research.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813204105621

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

RUSSIA: Freak weather spurs climate research

Nick Holdsworth
Russia=92s extreme summer weather is prompting the country=92s top scientis=
ts
to take climate change more seriously. A record-breaking heat wave,
hundreds of forest and peat bog fires, and smoke-induced smog stretching
for hundreds of kilometres around Moscow has turned central Russia into a
disaster zone in the past few weeks.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010081509430276

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SWEDEN: EU probes =91discriminatory=92 student selection

Ard Jongsma
Sweden=92s newly adopted university entrance selection process has come
under fire for discriminating against students from other Nordic countries
and the European Union. After receiving a complaint, the European
Commission has now asked the Swedish government for an explanation.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813203859516

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

EAST AFRICA: Honorary degrees =91abused=92 =96 claim

Gilbert Nganga
Universities in two East African countries, Kenya and Tanzania, have come
under fire for prolifically awarding honorary degrees =96 in some cases
allegedly for money and in others in return for influence.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813203745901
