WORLD ROUND-UP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

LIBYA: Professor at risk for exposing fake diplomas

Chained to a bed, under the close watch of police, Rasheed Mohamed Omar
El-Meheeshy was losing hope, writes Joshua Philipp for The Epoch Times.
Outside the hospital room in Libya, a group of angry students and faculty
were doing their all to force medical staff into denying treatment for
Meheeshy, and to have him returned to prison to die.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813201438142

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

PALESTINE: Authority orders release of academics

The Palestinian Authority on Wednesday ordered the release of seven
university lecturers and an administrative worker who were arrested the
week before for allegedly being affiliated with Hamas and trying to
establish a new university in the West Bank, writes Khaled Abu Toameh for
The Jerusalem Post.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813201322690

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: New survey to help improve student experience

Imagine a university where student numbers have doubled within five years,
writes Mary Hennock for The Chronicle of Higher Education. That is the
problem facing Inner Mongolia University of Science and Technology. Located
in the bleak industrial city of Baotou, a megacity built on mining, the
campus typifies the overstretched state of China=92s colleges, particularly
academically average ones.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813201221470

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SOUTH KOREA: Universities to set up overseas campuses

Students may in future be able to enrol at a local university in South
Korea and study both at home and abroad using its overseas campuses, writes
Bae Ji-sook for The Korea Times. This month the Ministry of Education,
Science and Technology gave prior notice of a law revision that would
enable domestic universities to more easily establish branches abroad.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813201122626

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Criminal minds betray academy=92s higher principles

As bad behaviour mars the US higher education sector, observers point to
the lack of an ethical code for all scholars, writes Jon Marcus for Times
Higher Education. A slew of criminal charges, civil lawsuits, expensive
legal settlements and other misdeeds by university managers and faculty in
the US suggest that the =91higher=92 in higher education no longer necessar=
ily
applies to moral standards.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813201029542

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SOUTH AFRICA: Cape Town urged to scrap race criteria

A university of Cape Town academic and struggle veteran wants the
university to scrap its medical students admission policy, saying it
discriminates against white, Indian and coloured (mixed-race) pupils,
writes Prega Govender for The Sunday Time.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100815094408364

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CANADA: Gender gap in professor salaries revealed

Male professors at Canadian universities on average earn higher salaries
than their female colleagues =96 with the discrepancy reaching more than
$20,000 at some institutions =96 according to numbers released last week by
Statistics Canada, reports Allison Cross for Postmedia News.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813200930781

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHILE: Women students now in the majority

Last year was the first time that a majority =96 51% =96 of all higher
education students in Chile were women, the Education Ministry has
reported, writes Kara Frantzich for the Santiago Times. =93This is a global
trend,=94 said Jaime Bellolio, an economist at the Jaime Guzm=E1n Foundatio=
n.
=93In developed countries this has happened, and Chile is a little behind.=
=94
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813200834439

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: California, postdoctoral researchers achieve pact

The fighting is over between the University of California and its staff of
6,500 highly educated but low-wage postdoctoral researchers, writes Nanette
Asimov for the San Francisco Chronicle.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813200641923

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Mental illness rises on campus, study finds

Severe mental illness is becoming more common on college and university
campuses in America, research suggests, reports CBC News. The percentage of
students with moderate to severe depression who sought counselling at a US
campus increased by 7% from 1998 to 2009, John Guthman, director of student
counselling services at Hofstra University in Hempstead, New York, said on
Thursday.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100813200531927



